      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Jerry Doyle (1898-1986) was an American editorial cartoonist. </p>
         <p>Doyle began his career in the newspaper industry while working as a messengar boy for
            the <emph render="italic"> Philadelphia Inquirer</emph>. Next he worked as a paste-up
            boy for the <emph render="italic">Public Ledger</emph>, before moving on to the <emph render="italic"> Philadelphia Record</emph> as its assistant art director.   In 1926, he joined the Merchant Marines for a time, before returning to the <emph render="italic">Record</emph> as its editorial cartoonist. Doyle continued as
            editorial cartoonist until the paper ceased publication in 1947. </p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Jerry Doyle Cartoons</emph> contains two original editorial cartoons composed for the <emph render="italic">Philadelphia Record</emph> sometime during the late 1930s or early 1940s.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
